<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by Ratt on 05-17-2001 04:32 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">*You will continue to post to this thread*
*You can not help yourself*
*Bad habits are hard to break*
*Don't fight the urge*

*Dangles a swinging coin in front of Midnight Essence*

I'm not trying to convince the other readers, my response was to YOU, not to them.

We have been debating the technical aspects of writing, not the amount of superfluous and "interesting" content I can provide.  I'm not an author of novels.  My writing is filled with the information I think is relevent, nothing more.  I'm sorry if it's 'uninteresting', but that doesn't negate the validity of it.

Fryfrog:

Quite a long dissertation there  :)  You seemed to have missed a few of my points, or perhaps you were referring to someone else, if so, then forget I mentioned anything.

I never said WTB, WTS, WTT, LFG, MOB, INC etc... were unacceptable, in fact, in some of my later posts I stated pretty much all the ones that were unacceptable (ne1, u, plz, ur, thx, plz, etc...)

Basically the words that only phonetically (and sometimes superfically) sound like the real word.  Contractions do not fall into this category, and acronyms do not either.  With the exception of INC, the above acronyms are just that, acronyms (WTT, WTB, LFG, etc...), whereas plz, thx, u, ur, etc... are just plain lazy.  They would either NOT sound like the word you are trying to say, if spoken, or they just look plain lazy and ridiculous.  

Additionally, I don't know how many times I can restatke this, but I do not harp on peoples occasional spelling or grammatical mistake, far from it.  I make them myself.  But I do _NOT_ use the terms "plz, thx, u, ur, b4, ne1" etc...  I DO use the terms LFG, MOB, I actually type out INCOMING (but that's another story), LFG.  I don't really sell/trade anything so I never use WTT/WTB/WTS.

The classifieds of a newspaper don't count.  I'm talking about the articles, written by "professional" writers.

As for your German bit, this isn't a primarily German forum, I wouldn't be posting here if it was, as I'm not German.  I also stated, a while back in this thread, that EAASL is exempt, but those individuals should still not be using plz, thx, u, ur, etc...

</TEXTAREA>
